## .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 8 — it's completely removed.
2. **`ThreadAbortException` will never be thrown** — your catch block is dead code.
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait for graceful completion with timeout (replaces Thread.Sleep + Abort)
        var actual = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(actual)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Task didn't finish in time — it's hung in unmanaged code or
            // a non-cancellable call. Log a warning; you cannot force-kill it.
            Log.Warning("Worker did not stop within {Timeout}", actual);
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a `Socket`, `Console.ReadLine`, etc., cancellation won't interrupt it. You **must** pass `CancellationToken` into the blocking API (or switch to async). |
| **No force-kill equivalent** | .NET 8 has no `Thread.Abort()` replacement. Design for cooperative cancellation or use `Process`-level isolation for untrusted work. |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | A `volatile` flag can't wake a thread blocked in I/O. `CancellationToken` integrates with `async` APIs, `WaitHandle`, and `Semaphore` to unblock waiters. |
| **Exception type changes** | Replace `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException)`. The `when` guard prevents swallowing unrelated cancellations. |
| **`ResetAbort` not needed** | `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception — no rethrow suppression required. |
| **Consider `BackgroundService`** | For hosted apps (ASP.NET Core, Worker Services), inherit from `BackgroundService` instead of hand-rolling this — it handles lifetime, DI, and cancellation for you. |

### If You Can't Make Calls Async

```csharp
// Wrap synchronous blocking calls with cancellation support
var item = await Task.Run(() => GetNextItem(), token);
```

> ⚠️ This doesn't truly cancel `GetNextItem()` — it just abandons the result. The call continues running on a thread pool thread. Only use this as a last resort during migration.
